#@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@
#***************************************************************************************
#*											*
#*		ChIPpip - an approchable ChIPseq pipeline for biologists		*
#*											*
#***************************************************************************************
#
#
# Follow the easy steps below to run ChIPpip
#---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# (1) 	Download the entire ChIPpip folder. 
#	Copy to any directory of your computer cluster. 
# 	The arborescence should look like this:
#
#	/<any_directory_of_your_cluster>/
#		└─ ChIPpipCreateNewProject.pl
#		└─ ChIPpipRunPipeline.pl
#		└─ README.txt
#		└─ scripts
#			└─ ChIPpip.pl
#			└─ ChIPpip.sh
#			└─ IterateSH.sh
#			└─ NewChIPseqProject
#				└─ DataStructure
#					└─ AdvancedSettings.txt
#					└─ Targets.txt
#				└─ fastq
#				└─ scripts
#			└─ PeakCalling.R
#			└─ QC.R
#			└─ QSUB_header.sh
#
#---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# (2)	Navigate to your <any_directory_of_your_cluster> and create a new project	
#
#		cd <any_directory_of_your_cluster>
#		perl ChIPpipCreateNewProject.pl /path/to/project 
#
#	This will prompt some messages about having created a new project
#
#---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# (3)	Fill in the Targets.txt file that is found in /path/to/project/DataStructure/Targets.txt.
#	You can either do this directly in the terminal or download the file using FTP.
#	
#	We advise to use a terminal text editor to modify your Targets.txt file. 
#	In a terminal window, type the following:
#
#		nano /path/to/project/DataStructure/Targets.txt
#
#	Edit the file to your need, specifying the paths, steps to execute, sample names, etc	
#	Make sure all samples are tab delimited (spaces will make the pipeline crash)
#
#	Save your changes by hitting the following keys:
#
#		ctrl-x   (followed by)   y   (and)   enter
#
#
#---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#	
# (4)	Run the pipeline
#
#		perl ChIPpipRunPipeline.pl /path/to/project
#
#
#	This will prompt a summary of the different paramters you fed to the pipeline.
#	Ensure all paths are correctly set and all files exist.
#	
#	You can follow the pipeline using the <qstat> command
#
#		qstat
#
#---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# (5)	Use the ChIPmE scripts to download necessary files to your local computer
#	and proceed to metagenic analysis
#
#
#---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# (Notes)	
#	
#	(i)	Ensure all files exist
#
#	(ii)	When filling in the Targets.txt file, ask your computer core for the following info:
#			- # Path_to_orifastq.gz		(this is where the sequencing core will stores your files)
#			- # Path_to_chrLens.dat		(some reference files corresponding to your genome of interest)
#			- # Path_to_RefGen.fa		(your reference genome fasta files)
#
#		To avoid changing these paths each time, modify the original Targets.txt.
#		This is required only once and can be done using the following command:
#			nano /<any_directory_of_your_cluster>/scripts/NewChIPseqProject/DataStructure/Targets.txt
#		
#		Modify and save your changes by typing:
#			ctrl-x   (followed by)   y   (and)   enter
#
#	(iii)	Specify alignment and filtering settings in: 
#			/path/to/project/DataStructure/AdvancedSettings.txt
#
#	(iv)	Aligned and filtered reads are stored in:
#			/path/to/project/bwa_saf/
#
#	(v)	Quality reports is stored in:
#			/path/to/project/QC/QCReport.pdf
#
#	(vi)	Jobs submitted to the cluster are stored in 
#			/path/to/project/scripts/
#
#	(vii)	Output and error logs of each job are found in
#			/path/to/project/scripts/<job>/qsub/
#
#	(viii)	Please report any bugs while using this pipeline. Thanks!
#
#
#
#---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
